2 Method
Let us consider a two-dimensional fluid layer embedded in three-dimensional space, see Fig. 1. The elements of the fluid flow tangentially to the layer and the layer itself can deform, exhibiting a velocity normal to the layer surface: we will denote the tangential and normal velocities above by v and w respectively. Geometrically speaking, the surface of the layer constitutes a differential manifold, which
we will denote by M. The velocity vi is a vector field in the tangent bundle of M, while w is a scalar field on M [20]. The surface tension of the layer is denoted by σ. Choosing—for example—the Monge
